\section{Introduction}
In the recent years, the nuclear reactions with unstable/weakly bound nuclei that have low breakup threshold and exotic structure has shown remarkable features that is different from those of tightly bound nuclei. It will be interesting to understand and revisit in detail, the difference in the reaction mechanisms using a tightly, weakly and unbound or halo nuclei. Very recently, a phenomenological comparison of reduced reaction cross sections of different reaction systems was proposed by using Wong¡¯s model \cite{bibitem1,bibitem2,bibitem3}. Several authors have extracted the quarter-point angle from the elastic scattering angular distribution reaction cross section, in order to compare the weakly and tightly bound projectiles \cite{bibitem4,bibitem5,bibitem6}. The quarter point angle which is also called the ¡°grazing angle¡± or ¡°rainbow angle¡± is one of the most conspicuous features of heavy-ion elastic scattering at above-barrier energies. Additionally, the sum of projectile and target radius is approximately equal to the classical apsidal distance or the distance of closest approach, evaluated at the energy for which the experimental cross section is one-quarter of the corresponding Rutherford cross section \cite{bibitem7}.

In the strong absorption model, the strong interaction region has been expressed by assuming a diffused edge with respect to the impact parameter and also by taking sharp cutoff angular momentum \cite{bibitem8}. The strong absorption radius $R_{s}$ has been introduced within the framework of the quarter-point angle that is the angle that separates the classically allowed region in angular range smaller than this angle from the classically forbidden region beyond it.

Experimentally, the nuclear radius (or nuclear matter distribution) can be determined by the measurement of electron scattering, isotope shift and interaction cross section etc. Since the electron is structure less and the electromagnetic interaction is very well known, therefore the charge distribution of a nucleus can be precisely obtained from the electron scattering measurements. The proton distribution can be deduced from the nuclear charge distribution in the case of stable nuclei. However, for an unstable nuclei being short-lived and difficult to use as a target, especially for the halo nuclei, one usually uses the isotope method or interaction cross section measurements to determine the size of nucleus. To be more precise, one can say that electron scattering is better than isotope shift and isotope shift is better than interaction cross section. Moreover the interaction cross section is much model dependent. From Fig.1, we can clearly see that the nuclear size is obviously correlated to the quarter-point angle. This is because x is a function of $R_{s}$, a kind of nuclear radius which is simply expressed as $A_{p}^{1/3} + A_{t}^{1/3}$. This indicates that we may extract the radius of unstable nuclei from the experimental quarter-point angle. This could be a new experimental method to determine the nuclear size.

As introduced above, the strong absorption radius can be extracted from the quarter-point angle through the elastic scattering angular distribution of the reacting system. Based on the concept of quarter-point angle, the main objective of this work is to compare the tightly, weakly bound (stable) and weakly bound (unstable) projectiles using the phenomenological formula for strong absorption radius. This difference of the three kinds of projectiles can be employed to find a better understanding of the strong absorption radius. Furthermore, nuclear radius can also be obtained from this analysis.

